WEBVTT

01:29.965 --> 01:32.675
LILLIAN: Just a little phase compensation.
MICHAEL: Yeah, yeah, yeah.

01:33.177 --> 01:34.969
I can see something.

01:35.220 --> 01:38.931
It's parts of the grid, but it's still rotating.
It's not locking up.

01:39.099 --> 01:41.267
HAL:
Maybe we all need a little break, Lillian.

01:41.435 --> 01:43.269
LILLIAN:
Hal, you take a break.

01:43.437 --> 01:45.438
Michael, we're almost there.

01:45.606 --> 01:46.898
How's that?

01:47.065 --> 01:51.527
MICHAEL: Yeah. It's getting better,
but it's still rotating. It's all scrambled.

01:52.654 --> 01:54.864
LILLIAN: How's that?
MICHAEL: It's better.

01:56.033 --> 01:57.325
Up the sync.

01:57.493 --> 02:00.787
LILLIAN:
Plus 25. Better?

02:00.954 --> 02:03.581
MICHAEL: I can sort of make out
more of the grid, but it's, ugh....

02:03.749 --> 02:05.333
I don't know.

02:05.501 --> 02:07.585
LILLIAN:
Maybe something's wrong with the grid.

02:07.795 --> 02:10.880
Hal, kill the grid.
And, Gordy, take a look around the lab.

02:18.430 --> 02:20.890
MICHAEL:
Oh, this is weird.

02:21.433 --> 02:23.601
Try something else.

02:24.061 --> 02:26.103
How's that?

02:26.271 --> 02:30.233
It's an image of the lab, but it's rotating.
It's all out of phase.

02:36.615 --> 02:38.074
LILLIAN:
I think I've got it.

02:38.242 --> 02:40.660
Gordy, go back to the grid for a second.

02:46.625 --> 02:48.417
A little more phase compensator.

02:49.253 --> 02:51.045
Up the sync signal.

02:51.213 --> 02:52.755
What do you see, angel?

02:52.965 --> 02:54.423
Clockwise rotation.

02:54.591 --> 02:57.093
It's still all scrambled.

02:57.427 --> 02:59.512
LILLIAN:
Okay, just a little more.

02:59.680 --> 03:03.015
Hold it a second. I think I got it.

03:03.600 --> 03:05.768
MICHAEL:
Hey, there it is. You got it.

03:05.936 --> 03:07.436
LILLIAN:
Okay, Hal, let's slate it.

03:07.604 --> 03:10.273
Gordy, follow Hal around with the slate.

03:17.406 --> 03:18.865
Hal, get the slate in there.

03:19.032 --> 03:20.616
I got it.

03:21.243 --> 03:23.286
Hold it one minute.

03:48.353 --> 03:50.730
Okay. Slate it.

04:01.408 --> 04:02.658
We've got speed.

04:02.826 --> 04:06.829
Test, October the 1 1 th,
1 0:41 p.m. Mark.

04:11.585 --> 04:12.877
To the kitchen.

04:13.045 --> 04:15.504
GORDY:
Good idea. Let's eat.

04:27.434 --> 04:28.809
Lou, what do you got for me?

04:28.977 --> 04:30.853
Here you go, Gordy. Everything you said.

04:31.021 --> 04:32.688
HAL: Slating.
-It's all bad.

04:32.856 --> 04:35.358
Hot and cold, sweet and sour.. .

04:35.525 --> 04:38.277
...chewy and melt-in-your-mouth and--

04:38.445 --> 04:40.029
Let's try something exotic.

04:40.197 --> 04:42.698
LOU:
You name it, Gordy.

04:42.866 --> 04:45.826
-A little steak.
-A little steak coming up.

04:45.994 --> 04:47.370
GORDY:
Peanut butter.

04:47.537 --> 04:48.871
Peanut butter.

04:49.039 --> 04:51.123
Hot fudge.

04:51.291 --> 04:52.541
Hot fudge?

04:52.709 --> 04:55.753
GORDY: A few nuts.
-A few nuts.

04:55.921 --> 04:58.255
GORDY:
And some marshmallow sauce.

04:58.423 --> 05:00.049
-Heh-heh-heh.
-Marshmallow sauce.

05:00.217 --> 05:01.467
And put a cherry on top.

05:02.427 --> 05:05.805
Man, marshmallow and cherry on steak?

05:05.973 --> 05:08.724
What in the world
have you been drinking?

05:08.892 --> 05:12.019
HAL: What's he been smoking?
-Mmm, mmm.

05:21.071 --> 05:23.072
[KEYBOARD PLAYING]

05:24.783 --> 05:25.908
GORDY:
Hey.

05:26.076 --> 05:28.744
Hey, spaceman,
welcome back to planet Earth.

05:28.912 --> 05:32.415
GORDY: What you see before you is the
latest fashion in full-sensory gratification.

05:32.582 --> 05:33.916
-Come on, give us a kiss.
-No.

05:34.084 --> 05:36.252
GORDY: Come on.
-No. Come on, let's go back to work.

05:36.420 --> 05:38.170
-Gordy, go on.
GORDY: For science.

05:38.338 --> 05:40.006
Gordy, try to contain yourself.

05:40.757 --> 05:43.300
-This is a test.
-Come on.

05:44.594 --> 05:47.888
Andrea, give us a 90d Bf
in sine wave, please.

05:48.056 --> 05:50.099
Okay, I'm ready.

05:52.394 --> 05:53.936
Slate.

05:56.523 --> 05:58.524
[KEYBOARD PLAYS NOTE]

06:12.456 --> 06:14.707
Gordy, this is not on our itinerary.

06:14.875 --> 06:17.334
GORDY:
Just a few seconds. I think I got an idea.

06:17.502 --> 06:18.794
MAN:
Well, hi, Hal. How are you?

06:18.962 --> 06:22.131
-What are you guys up to, anyway?
-Just wanna see my old buddy Lena.

06:24.968 --> 06:26.552
[GIBBERING]

06:27.054 --> 06:28.304
How are you, Lena, honey?

06:29.639 --> 06:30.973
Aw.

06:31.892 --> 06:35.436
Lena, I know what it's like
to be guinea pig.

06:43.945 --> 06:46.989
Is her output on standard interface?

06:47.157 --> 06:48.908
Regular plug.

06:51.578 --> 06:53.370
I don't know.. ..

06:54.331 --> 06:55.831
Perfect mate for Dr. Brace.

06:55.999 --> 06:58.334
I don't know if that's such a good idea.

06:58.585 --> 06:59.794
Ha.

06:59.961 --> 07:02.630
MAN: That's not so funny, Gordy.
GORDY: Come in, Lena.

07:02.798 --> 07:04.799
[STATIC AND LENA GIBBERING]

07:07.094 --> 07:09.095
[INAUDIBLE DIALOGUE]

07:10.138 --> 07:11.180
Lena.

07:12.974 --> 07:14.975
[BEEPING]

07:18.021 --> 07:19.688
LILLIAN:
Michael?

07:21.775 --> 07:23.359
Michael?

07:26.363 --> 07:28.030
Michael.

07:29.783 --> 07:31.534
Michael!

07:32.369 --> 07:33.661
What did you do?

07:33.829 --> 07:37.248
Nothing. Just a little experiment
in animal behavior.

07:37.415 --> 07:39.416
[SNARLING]

07:41.837 --> 07:45.256
There's something wrong with you.
You know that?

07:45.549 --> 07:47.216
You didn't like Lena.

07:47.384 --> 07:49.635
LILLIAN: What happened?
MICHAEL: Nothing.

07:50.637 --> 07:53.305
-So?
-I'm telling you, it works.

07:53.473 --> 07:56.725
-The tests? Sound? Taste? Smell?
-Everything, everything.

07:56.893 --> 07:59.645
-One hundred percent. In fact, better.
-What did you taste?

07:59.813 --> 08:01.939
Steak, overdone. Right?

08:02.107 --> 08:05.860
Peanut butter, hot fudge sauce,
slight orange flavor.

08:06.027 --> 08:07.736
-Disgusting.
-Nuts?

08:07.904 --> 08:09.822
Walnuts. I hate them.

08:10.490 --> 08:11.532
That's it?

08:12.409 --> 08:13.826
Marshmallow.

08:13.994 --> 08:16.453
-Cherry on the top.
-That's it, man.

08:16.621 --> 08:19.331
-How do you feel now?
-Like a glass of champagne.

08:19.499 --> 08:21.709
-Get some glasses.
GORDY: All right.

08:22.335 --> 08:24.378
Congratulations.

08:25.088 --> 08:26.172
MICHAEL:
What's this?

08:26.339 --> 08:28.090
One lousy beer.

08:29.426 --> 08:31.802
I would like to make a toast.

08:31.970 --> 08:34.555
To the one who never gives up.

08:35.849 --> 08:37.600
Lillian Reynolds. ..

08:37.767 --> 08:41.937
...E.E., M.D., Ph.D. ..

08:43.106 --> 08:44.565
...B.M.T. ..

08:45.483 --> 08:48.861
...B.V.D., R.S.V.P., COD.

08:49.487 --> 08:51.113
My friend.

08:52.949 --> 08:57.411
Cheers.

08:57.746 --> 08:59.747
[MAN SPEAKING INDISTINCTLY
ON TV]

09:06.463 --> 09:08.464
[PEOPLE LAUGHING ON TV]

09:11.968 --> 09:13.969
[OPERA MUSIC PLAYING
OVER SPEAKERS]

09:33.657 --> 09:35.157
LILLIAN:
Night.

10:36.428 --> 10:38.429
[MUSICIANS PLAYING
CLASSICAL MUSIC]

10:52.610 --> 10:54.069
CHRIS:
Hi, Dad.

10:54.237 --> 10:55.446
Hi, Mike.

10:55.613 --> 10:57.990
You worked late.
Did you have a good day?

10:59.576 --> 11:00.576
Hello, Barry.

11:24.017 --> 11:26.352
MAN [IN DISTANCE]:
Let's go on to the last movement.

11:40.658 --> 11:42.451
Success.

11:42.619 --> 11:44.286
We made it.

11:54.339 --> 11:55.631
ALEX:
Talented man, your husband.

11:56.633 --> 12:01.136
Impossible at times, but talented.
What do you think? Can you handle it?

12:01.304 --> 12:03.263
Yes, I think I can, uh....

12:03.431 --> 12:06.934
I think I can get it down to size
and make it look attractive.

12:07.394 --> 12:09.144
Maybe something like.. .

12:09.312 --> 12:10.813
...stereo headphones.

12:10.980 --> 12:13.107
Oh, I'm not worried about that.
I know you can.

12:13.274 --> 12:14.942
It's Michael.

12:15.777 --> 12:18.695
You're gonna have to work
very closely with him.

12:18.863 --> 12:19.988
Is that a problem?

12:20.365 --> 12:21.740
No.

12:21.908 --> 12:24.076
-That won't be any problem.
-Good.

12:24.244 --> 12:25.285
Not for me.

12:26.162 --> 12:29.998
-Hal, I'm gonna kill you after this.
-You don't understand. It's part of my--

12:30.166 --> 12:32.292
-It's slow and agonizing.
-Why are you upset?

12:32.460 --> 12:34.503
-Part of my job.
-It's not part of your job.

12:34.671 --> 12:36.088
I know what you wanted to do.

12:36.256 --> 12:38.590
-Grease yourself with the boss.
HAL: I did not.

12:38.758 --> 12:41.385
Why don't you wait and see
what he has to say?

12:41.553 --> 12:43.929
Why don't you grow up?

12:45.849 --> 12:47.599
Be careful.

12:50.645 --> 12:53.021
I hate this junk.

12:54.983 --> 12:56.525
ALEX:
Hello, Michael.

12:56.693 --> 12:58.318
Good to see you.

12:58.486 --> 13:00.737
ALEX: Lillian.
-Hello, Alex. How are you?

13:00.905 --> 13:03.031
-Hi, Lillian.
-How are you?

13:03.199 --> 13:05.576
Well, won't you sit down?

13:09.289 --> 13:11.373
Well, congratulations.

13:11.541 --> 13:13.167
For what?

13:13.710 --> 13:15.377
Hal said you had a breakthrough.

13:17.547 --> 13:18.964
Well, Hal's crazy.

13:21.593 --> 13:23.719
Did you have a breakthrough or not?

13:26.014 --> 13:27.139
Yes.

13:30.310 --> 13:34.563
Alex, dear, it was just another test.
A little better, but still crude.

13:35.523 --> 13:36.732
What's the big problem?

13:37.859 --> 13:41.737
The superconductors have to be chilled
to 270 below to work.

13:41.905 --> 13:43.572
The whole thing's too big and heavy.

13:44.908 --> 13:49.578
Your hotshots, Evans and Wetmore,
failed on that one year after year.

13:54.292 --> 13:56.752
Courtesy, Evans-Wetmore.

14:00.048 --> 14:02.883
It's a superconducting chip.
No cooling needed.

14:04.010 --> 14:05.719
When did they do this?

14:05.887 --> 14:09.389
You need it, it's yours. Keep it quiet.

14:09.974 --> 14:12.434
Data-processing division
will go through the roof.. .

14:12.602 --> 14:15.145
...with the high-speed computer
applications of that.

14:15.313 --> 14:18.857
Karen has expressed enthusiasm
to help us market it and package it.

14:19.025 --> 14:20.859
Alex, I think you're moving too fast.

14:21.819 --> 14:24.071
You haven't even seen it yet.

14:24.239 --> 14:27.533
There's more to it
than just practical applications...

14:27.700 --> 14:29.117
...and packaging.

14:30.495 --> 14:32.079
Lillian. ..

14:32.956 --> 14:35.040
... I know you can do it.

14:35.792 --> 14:38.126
I know you can do it.

14:39.254 --> 14:41.255
I'd like a demonstration.

14:41.422 --> 14:43.215
I want you.. .

14:43.383 --> 14:47.761
...to knock my socks off. Okay?

14:48.304 --> 14:50.305
[CHUCKLES]

14:52.809 --> 14:53.976
Good.

14:56.688 --> 14:57.854
And thanks.

14:58.022 --> 14:59.898
Don't lose that.

15:02.151 --> 15:04.069
You did it again, Alex.

15:04.529 --> 15:06.321
-Michael.
-Thank you.

15:06.489 --> 15:09.491
Any problem working with, uh, Karen?

15:11.953 --> 15:14.997
No. Not for me.

15:15.832 --> 15:17.874
Thanks, Mike.

15:21.713 --> 15:23.338
MICHAEL:
Chris.

15:23.715 --> 15:24.756
Chris.

15:24.924 --> 15:27.509
I told you to get out of the pool.
He pays no attention.

15:27.677 --> 15:29.428
I'll get him, honey.

15:30.680 --> 15:33.015
-Chris.
-Hurry up.

15:33.182 --> 15:35.017
-Dr. Brace.
-Chris.

15:35.184 --> 15:38.186
Dr. Brace, I'd like to introduce
Dr. Harris and Dr. Bock.

15:38.354 --> 15:39.730
-Call me Ted.
-Ted.

15:39.897 --> 15:41.898
-Janet.
MICHAEL: Hello.

15:43.776 --> 15:45.193
You saw the house before.

15:45.361 --> 15:47.779
Yeah, we're sold.
We just wanna get all the details.

15:47.947 --> 15:49.781
-We signed all the papers today.
-Good.

15:49.949 --> 15:51.742
-That's for you.
-Hey, Dad, is that it?

15:51.909 --> 15:55.203
-That's what you wanted.
-All right. You got the right one.

15:55.622 --> 15:57.664
Say thank you.

16:00.126 --> 16:01.918
As you can see.. .

16:03.046 --> 16:05.881
...this is a very special house.

16:07.133 --> 16:09.635
I spent a lot of time to get it right.

16:12.013 --> 16:13.889
Why don't you show them
the secret closet?

16:14.057 --> 16:15.724
Good idea. Right this way.

16:15.892 --> 16:19.770
The house is wonderful.
Ted loves all the special things you've done.

16:21.606 --> 16:23.315
Do you like them?

16:23.483 --> 16:24.983
KAREN:
No.

16:25.985 --> 16:29.071
-It's theirs now.
-I know.

16:31.532 --> 16:33.659
I can't stay here now.

16:34.327 --> 16:38.580
Oh, well, that's okay. I can, uh,
take care of all the packing and stuff.

16:39.749 --> 16:41.041
-You sure?
-Sure.

16:41.209 --> 16:43.168
It's a lot to do.

16:43.836 --> 16:45.253
Do you have cardboard boxes?

16:46.255 --> 16:48.256
Yes, I have cardboard boxes.

16:48.841 --> 16:51.093
I can take care of it all. Don't worry.

16:53.971 --> 16:55.722
You could go live over at the center.

16:56.391 --> 16:59.601
-Lillian's there.
-Mm-hm.

17:05.942 --> 17:07.943
WOMAN [OVER RADIO]:
This is Flight Simulation Lab Control.

17:08.111 --> 17:10.028
Sold your house yet?

17:11.197 --> 17:13.490
-Yep.
WOMAN: All flight data....

17:13.658 --> 17:16.535
I keep telling you
the rooms at the center are so cheap.

17:16.703 --> 17:17.744
I know.

17:17.912 --> 17:23.917
At 9:38 p.m., pilot Gordon Forbes is
performing a low-level simulated assault.

17:25.878 --> 17:29.131
WOMAN [OVER PA]:
Range, 1 00 yards and closing.

17:30.425 --> 17:31.925
Ninety-five.

17:32.927 --> 17:36.555
Ninety. Simulated altitude, 600 feet.

17:37.265 --> 17:39.975
Ground speed, 51 2 knots.

17:40.143 --> 17:43.729
Assault range, 85.

17:44.647 --> 17:46.106
Eighty.

17:46.274 --> 17:49.276
HAL:
It's not worth it, Gordy. Don't do it.

17:51.738 --> 17:53.155
Uh, Pilot Forbes, you're.. .

17:53.322 --> 17:54.573
...off of the simulation.

17:55.158 --> 17:57.409
Sweet target in sight.

17:58.995 --> 18:00.912
Dr. Reynolds, Dr. Brace...

18:01.080 --> 18:03.874
...your pilot has lost control.

18:08.379 --> 18:09.504
GORDY: Okay?
-Okay, Gordy.

18:09.672 --> 18:10.672
GORDY: Helmet's on?
-Go.

18:10.840 --> 18:13.842
GORDY:
Contact. Okay, let's get in.

18:14.010 --> 18:15.427
Right, down.

18:15.595 --> 18:19.973
-Okay, then seat belts, right.
-Okay, Gordy. Hit it.

18:20.141 --> 18:22.684
GORDY:
Brake, gas pedal. Let's go.

18:26.355 --> 18:28.064
WOMAN 1 :
Come on.

18:29.108 --> 18:31.276
WOMAN 2:
Come on, Gordy.

18:31.444 --> 18:34.279
MAN: Come on. Come on, let's go.
WOMAN 2: Come on.

18:34.447 --> 18:36.782
GORDY: Yeah, I'm coming.
Wait a minute. Wait a minute.

18:36.949 --> 18:39.701
Tallyho. Here we go.

18:41.120 --> 18:44.456
-I'm gonna die. I'm freezing!
GORDY: You're gonna make history.

18:44.624 --> 18:46.583
So it's chilly. It's gonna be great.

18:46.751 --> 18:48.293
WOMAN 1 :
Talk him out of this one. It's too cold.

18:49.420 --> 18:51.421
[WOMEN SHRIEKING AND GIGGLING]

18:54.550 --> 18:56.426
Come on. One more time for science.

18:56.594 --> 18:58.762
It's getting ready to rain. Let's go home.

18:58.930 --> 19:02.516
-Too cold. It's not even--
GORDY: Come on, come on.

19:02.683 --> 19:05.393
One more time. Come on.
Yeah, yeah, yeah.

19:05.561 --> 19:07.312
WOMAN 2:
You didn't see me up there--

19:07.480 --> 19:08.980
GORDY:
Come on.

19:09.148 --> 19:11.149
[WOMEN SHRIEKING]

19:16.072 --> 19:17.072
[CHUCKLING]

19:20.660 --> 19:22.661
[LAUGHING]

19:23.079 --> 19:25.622
KAREN: Nobody is gonna put
a thing like that on their head.

19:25.790 --> 19:28.792
It's gotta be pared down
to the absolute essentials.

19:28.960 --> 19:32.254
Just enough to house the sensors.
You know, it can't look intimidating.

19:32.421 --> 19:33.839
What do I care what it looks like?

19:34.006 --> 19:36.007
[BEEPING]

19:39.762 --> 19:41.304
Put a chip here...

19:41.472 --> 19:43.223
...another here.. .

19:43.391 --> 19:44.808
...here. ..

19:44.976 --> 19:48.144
...an op-amp, spread flat across.
That's all. Just do it.

19:48.312 --> 19:51.189
-Put the rest of the stuff remote.
MICHAEL: Sure.

19:53.317 --> 19:55.318
[BEEPING]

20:10.126 --> 20:11.293
How's that?

20:11.919 --> 20:13.253
It's good.

20:13.421 --> 20:15.422
Good night, all.

20:26.726 --> 20:28.685
[ENGINE ROARING]

20:34.817 --> 20:36.818
[ENGINES ROARING]

20:55.004 --> 20:57.339
WOMAN 1: Don't fall!
MAN 1: Hang on, Gordy!

20:57.506 --> 20:59.215
WOMAN 1 : Come on, Gordy!
MAN 2: Go!

20:59.383 --> 21:02.427
-Way to go!
WOMAN 2: Get that horse moving!

21:05.181 --> 21:07.182
[WOMEN SHRIEKING]

21:18.027 --> 21:20.111
ALEX:
Oh, God.

21:21.781 --> 21:22.948
That's remarkable.

21:23.115 --> 21:26.660
A true one-of-a-kind
scientific breakthrough.

21:26.827 --> 21:30.705
Oh, God, that's wonderful.
We'll have to tell the division heads.

21:30.873 --> 21:34.209
And, Karen, maybe we can modify it
and simplify it even a little more?

21:34.377 --> 21:37.462
-Oh, yes. That's already in the works.
ALEX: Good.

21:38.047 --> 21:39.506
We'll need to make a demo tape.

21:39.674 --> 21:43.218
We wanna show the potential
for travel and education and news.

21:44.345 --> 21:48.390
-Can we do that in the conference room?
-We could pump it right through the phone.

21:48.557 --> 21:50.684
ALEX:
Excellent. And thank you all.

21:50.851 --> 21:55.021
You've blown communication
as we've known it right out of the water.

21:55.856 --> 22:00.026
And I'm very proud of all of you.
You blew my socks off.

22:01.404 --> 22:03.405
I think he likes it.

22:10.204 --> 22:12.580
MAN:
All right.

22:14.500 --> 22:16.501
[CHATTERING]

22:36.397 --> 22:38.023
It's great.

22:40.401 --> 22:41.985
Really?

22:42.778 --> 22:45.447
-It's great.
-Good.

22:46.073 --> 22:47.699
I'm glad you like it.

22:51.537 --> 22:52.579
You know.. .

22:52.747 --> 22:54.622
...we never worked together before.

22:56.959 --> 23:01.254
I always tried to avoid that, you know?

23:08.262 --> 23:10.263
[BEEPING]

23:14.977 --> 23:16.644
[PEOPLE SCREAMING]

23:59.772 --> 24:01.773
[HORN HONKING]

24:20.376 --> 24:22.377
[HELICOPTER WHIRRING]

25:50.883 --> 25:53.051
ALEX:
Sorry about that, ladies.

25:53.302 --> 25:55.303
[PEOPLE GROANING AND CHATTERING]

26:13.072 --> 26:14.864
MAN 1 : Hey.
MAN 2: Hey.

26:15.199 --> 26:18.034
-Here you go.
-Thank you.

26:19.161 --> 26:22.163
Well? So tell me about it.

26:22.331 --> 26:24.374
-The damnedest thing I've ever felt.
-Yeah?

26:24.541 --> 26:26.668
Knocked my socks off.

26:26.835 --> 26:28.127
What was it like?

26:28.295 --> 26:29.837
Like you were there.

26:30.005 --> 26:33.091
Taste, smell, everything.

26:33.259 --> 26:34.509
Incredible.

26:34.677 --> 26:37.512
I even feel like I just ate.

26:37.680 --> 26:40.765
What about, um, military application?

26:40.933 --> 26:42.475
It's wide open.

26:43.143 --> 26:44.852
Missile guidance? That kind of thing?

26:45.020 --> 26:48.147
Jim, they're gonna be able to plug
right into the old noodle.

26:49.358 --> 26:50.525
Hm.

27:08.377 --> 27:10.378
[BAND PLAYING JAZZ MUSIC]

27:10.713 --> 27:15.717
-This is for us?
-Just you, just me.

27:15.884 --> 27:17.051
[CHATTERING]

27:17.219 --> 27:18.469
Just for us.

27:18.637 --> 27:22.056
MAN: Congratulations, you guys.
-Hello.

27:22.599 --> 27:23.641
This is great.

27:23.809 --> 27:27.228
I've never had so many people
wanna talk to me before in my life.

27:27.396 --> 27:30.440
-That's because you're famous.
-Oh, God. You love it.

27:30.607 --> 27:31.774
I do.

27:31.942 --> 27:34.068
You're good-looking too.

27:35.487 --> 27:38.114
Hey, get me a light, will you?

27:39.491 --> 27:42.744
MICHAEL: Can I borrow that?
-Sure. Here.

27:46.165 --> 27:47.915
You smoke too much.

27:48.083 --> 27:51.252
I know I do. I know I do.

27:55.257 --> 27:56.883
ALEX: How you doing?
LILLIAN: We're doing fine.

27:57.051 --> 28:01.596
Listen, I got some people I want you
to meet upstairs in a few minutes, okay?

28:01.764 --> 28:03.931
You're my stars. I wanna show you off.

28:04.099 --> 28:06.559
I'll have Hal come back and get you.

28:06.727 --> 28:08.603
Don't disappoint me.

28:09.355 --> 28:13.441
A few people upstairs.
That's it. That's it.

28:13.609 --> 28:15.943
Yeah. Mm-hm.

28:17.071 --> 28:20.323
-Hi, Lillian.
LILLIAN: Hi. How are you?

28:20.491 --> 28:22.450
-Hi.
-Good to see you. Hi.

28:22.618 --> 28:24.619
Well, I'll see you.

28:24.787 --> 28:26.788
KAREN:
Barry, I’d love some more white wine.

28:26.955 --> 28:28.414
-Sure.
-Ah, yes, some drinks.

28:29.041 --> 28:31.250
I'll call you tomorrow, Wendy.

28:31.835 --> 28:34.879
-You look nice.
-Thank you.

28:39.009 --> 28:40.134
Thanks.

28:40.302 --> 28:42.428
Why do you still see him?

28:42.596 --> 28:46.974
Because he's a perfectly wonderful,
thoughtful, uncreative guy.

28:48.519 --> 28:49.644
[WOMAN SHOUTS INDISTINCTLY]

28:49.812 --> 28:51.479
Congratulations, Michael.

28:51.647 --> 28:54.982
You must be proud to be married
to such a brilliant man.

28:55.150 --> 28:56.651
-Thank you.
-Thank you.

28:56.819 --> 28:58.820
He never spoke to me before.

28:58.987 --> 29:01.697
It's good to see you
enjoying yourself so much.

29:02.157 --> 29:03.157
For you.

29:03.325 --> 29:05.451
I'll see you later, upstairs.

29:09.665 --> 29:12.208
This is the result of teamwork,
gentlemen.

29:12.376 --> 29:17.255
A group of brilliant, creative scientists
cocooned for 1 0 years in a laboratory. ..

29:17.423 --> 29:19.841
...without outside intervention.

29:20.426 --> 29:22.718
My job has been to protect
that environment.

29:22.886 --> 29:27.181
That lab is sacred ground,
and with due respect to you all...

29:27.349 --> 29:31.144
... I don't wanna muddy it with any boots
from outside, military or civilian.

29:31.311 --> 29:35.606
That's all very well, Dr. Terson,
but we paid for that cocoon.

29:35.774 --> 29:38.025
I think we have every right
to know what goes on.

29:38.193 --> 29:39.819
I accept that responsibility, sir.

29:39.987 --> 29:42.697
I'm not talking about
a military or civilian potential now.

29:42.865 --> 29:44.949
I am talking about a breakthrough.

29:45.117 --> 29:48.119
A communications breakthrough.

29:48.287 --> 29:49.954
Words don't do it.

29:50.122 --> 29:52.540
Pictures don't do it. This...

29:52.708 --> 29:54.083
...might be the beginning.

29:54.251 --> 29:58.129
But you've got to let my people breathe.

29:58.297 --> 30:00.339
You've got to-- Ahem.

30:00.507 --> 30:02.341
Well, here they are.

30:02.509 --> 30:04.927
COLONEL:
Lillian, good to see you again.

30:05.095 --> 30:06.888
I didn't see you downstairs, colonel.

30:07.055 --> 30:10.892
Well, we all just got in,
and we can only stay a few minutes.

30:11.518 --> 30:13.186
Captain Barty.

30:13.353 --> 30:15.146
Mr. Zimbach.

30:15.314 --> 30:16.981
-Colonel Easterbrook.
-How do you do?

30:17.149 --> 30:21.486
-And Landon Marks.
-It's a real, real pleasure, Dr. Reynolds.

30:21.653 --> 30:25.907
-Do I know you?
-Yes. Caltech, '56.

30:26.074 --> 30:28.659
I wanted you all
to get to know each other.

30:28.827 --> 30:30.411
Dr. Reynolds, of course.

30:30.579 --> 30:31.913
Karen Brace.

30:32.080 --> 30:33.706
-Dr. Brace.
-Very nice design.

30:33.874 --> 30:36.417
-Thank you.
-And Mr. Abramson.

30:42.508 --> 30:45.927
We're tremendously enthusiastic
about your recent breakthrough.

30:46.094 --> 30:49.055
Yes, we've been working
on an array system ourselves. ..

30:49.223 --> 30:50.681
...but with slow progress.

30:50.849 --> 30:53.017
That's understandable.

30:53.185 --> 30:55.770
COLONEL: Of course, we've been looking
at the application...

30:55.938 --> 30:58.272
...from a different point of view.

30:58.440 --> 31:01.776
What point of view is that, colonel?
Blowing people to kingdom come?

31:02.277 --> 31:03.694
[LAUGHING]

31:06.615 --> 31:10.910
Lillian, I think we can let
the colonel express his opinion.

31:12.663 --> 31:14.455
Well.. .

31:14.623 --> 31:17.416
...not everything in the military
is blowing people up.

31:17.584 --> 31:20.419
We're interested in tapping
into higher brain functions.

31:20.587 --> 31:23.798
Thoughts, emotions, that kind of thing.

31:25.217 --> 31:26.801
Now I remember you.

31:27.344 --> 31:29.762
We're working on that too.

31:30.847 --> 31:32.932
Shut up, Michael.

31:35.769 --> 31:38.437
You don't know
what's going on, do you?

31:40.148 --> 31:41.983
Why don't we all have a drink?

31:43.652 --> 31:45.987
-I don't get it.
LILLIAN: No, you don't.

31:46.154 --> 31:48.322
Excuse me.

31:54.871 --> 31:59.875
Lillian, I don't think Dr. Marks' presence
will be a detriment to the project.

32:00.043 --> 32:02.420
Alex, I'm sorry.

32:02.588 --> 32:04.630
No. I have to say no.

32:04.798 --> 32:08.509
MARKS: Dr. Reynolds, for your own sake,
I'd like to help you complete your records.

32:08.677 --> 32:11.637
A woman of your stature
can't just sloppily jot down--

32:11.805 --> 32:14.682
Alex, please.
You promised you wouldn't do this.

32:14.850 --> 32:17.351
He's a spy for the feds.

32:17.519 --> 32:21.647
The feds, as you call it,
are here to protect the American public.. .

32:21.815 --> 32:23.816
...from potentially dangerous research.

32:23.984 --> 32:26.152
Alex, no. No.

32:26.320 --> 32:30.948
I want you to understand, Dr. Reynolds,
that my function is not to be a spy.

32:31.116 --> 32:33.034
I do have a certain expertise.

32:33.201 --> 32:35.828
Listen, you were a hack at Stanford
and a hack at Bell.

32:35.996 --> 32:38.080
-He's on your team.
-Why?

32:38.248 --> 32:40.708
-He is on your team.
-No.

32:40.876 --> 32:43.961
-Lillian, goddamn it, the man just wants--
-Alex.

32:44.129 --> 32:46.672
Don't "goddamn" me, sweetheart.

32:46.840 --> 32:48.466
-Just don't "goddamn" me.
-Come on.

32:48.634 --> 32:51.052
And don't take my project.

32:52.054 --> 32:54.180
This is my project.

32:54.348 --> 32:58.309
And I don't want to see it end up
on some defense scrap heap.. .

32:58.477 --> 33:00.561
...before we know what it's really about.

33:01.271 --> 33:04.398
You have no idea.

33:13.075 --> 33:14.659
Well.. ..

33:16.036 --> 33:17.078
I'm sorry.

33:33.261 --> 33:35.262
[GROANING]

33:41.770 --> 33:44.605
You're gonna spoil the whole thing.

33:45.565 --> 33:49.110
-Oh, you're so stupid.
-I wanna tell you something.

33:49.277 --> 33:51.445
I don't like the way you treat me.

33:51.613 --> 33:53.280
You keep calling this thing "mine."

33:53.448 --> 33:57.284
I've been next to you from the start.
It's mine too, so don't do that.

33:57.452 --> 33:59.954
-Oh, you don't get it.
ALEX: Lillian?

34:00.122 --> 34:02.123
-Keep him out. Keep him out.
-Go.

34:02.290 --> 34:05.209
I have tried to keep those people
off your back, but you've--

34:05.377 --> 34:06.627
What is it?

34:06.795 --> 34:09.213
-Are you--?
-I'm fine. I'll be fine.

34:09.381 --> 34:12.508
ALEX: You look bad.
-Oh, thanks.

34:12.676 --> 34:14.051
ALEX:
You want a doctor?

34:14.219 --> 34:15.594
I am a doctor.

34:15.762 --> 34:17.847
What's going on? Are you crazy?

34:18.014 --> 34:22.351
This is the ladies' room.
It's the ladies' room.

34:23.478 --> 34:25.479
Can I help you?

34:26.481 --> 34:29.567
It makes me sick when I lose my temper.

34:46.001 --> 34:48.127
GORDY: Here she is.
-I don't want that thing, Gordy.

34:48.295 --> 34:50.629
Hal, I can't believe
that you didn't know about it.

34:50.797 --> 34:52.673
Everybody at the party played it.

34:53.175 --> 34:55.634
Now, you don't wanna
get left behind, Hal.

34:55.802 --> 34:57.303
Hey, this is hot.

34:57.471 --> 34:59.305
[CHUCKLING]

35:00.682 --> 35:03.517
It sure beats dirty magazines.

35:03.685 --> 35:05.686
[CHUCKLING]

35:07.981 --> 35:09.190
Yeah, thank you, Gordy.

35:12.652 --> 35:14.236
Hey, enjoy yourself.

35:14.404 --> 35:16.530
Yeah, sure.

35:23.997 --> 35:26.123
-You're crazy. No!
GORDY: Come on, let's do it.

35:26.291 --> 35:29.293
-Let's do it for science, baby.
-Science. Sure, I can trust you.

35:29.461 --> 35:31.420
I'm not gonna do it.
Anybody can come in.

35:31.588 --> 35:34.381
GORDY: Lillian won't be back tonight.
I promise. She won't be back.

35:34.549 --> 35:36.550
-You promise?
GORDY: Come on, I promise.

35:36.718 --> 35:39.553
Come on, babe.

35:40.555 --> 35:42.389
All right.

36:50.500 --> 36:52.334
Are these real?

36:52.502 --> 36:54.211
I hope so.

36:56.923 --> 36:58.632
This is it.

37:12.480 --> 37:13.981
What do you call this?

37:14.149 --> 37:15.482
We call it "the Hat."

37:16.818 --> 37:18.986
What do you do with it?

37:19.154 --> 37:21.322
Put it on your head.

37:26.661 --> 37:28.871
Come on, Chris. Hands off.

37:31.750 --> 37:33.334
What's it for?

37:33.501 --> 37:37.004
With a thing like that, you could finish
the seventh grade in five minutes.

37:37.172 --> 37:38.964
Okay. Start it up.

37:40.842 --> 37:42.635
Not today.

37:45.013 --> 37:46.347
Hmm.

37:47.432 --> 37:49.183
What's that?

37:50.143 --> 37:51.518
I don't know.

37:52.354 --> 37:54.355
MICHAEL:
Scan sync's on.

37:54.522 --> 37:56.398
LILLIAN: You got that?
-Mm-hm.

37:58.360 --> 37:59.860
Interlock's open.

38:00.028 --> 38:02.279
-Okay.
-Okay?

38:02.739 --> 38:03.948
It's hot off the mold.

38:04.115 --> 38:05.950
Take a look.

38:07.452 --> 38:09.036
MICHAEL:
Looks great.

38:09.204 --> 38:11.038
Sit, please.

38:11.206 --> 38:12.831
KAREN:
"Looks great. Sit, please."

38:12.999 --> 38:15.960
Now, just empty your head.

38:16.127 --> 38:18.212
Empty my head?

38:20.256 --> 38:21.966
Okay?

38:22.133 --> 38:23.342
Relax.

38:25.553 --> 38:27.805
Empty my head and relax.

38:33.144 --> 38:37.064
Just lean back and forget everything.
It'll be okay.

38:51.955 --> 38:53.539
That's good.

39:15.395 --> 39:18.439
KAREN:
It's hot off the mold. Take a look.

39:24.946 --> 39:26.780
Relax.

39:27.574 --> 39:31.368
You can take the house, the kid, the car,
the whole goddamn thing.

39:31.536 --> 39:34.371
I don't want anything. I'll live in a hotel.

39:37.208 --> 39:39.752
What about my work?
I can't live like this, Karen.

39:40.170 --> 39:41.211
Go.

39:43.631 --> 39:45.591
Why don't you just go?

39:52.182 --> 39:55.434
Take the house, take the car.

39:55.602 --> 39:57.186
I'll go to a hotel.

39:57.353 --> 40:01.315
I can't live like this, Karen.
You're strangling me.

40:01.483 --> 40:03.984
What are you talking about,
you can't live like this?

40:04.152 --> 40:06.612
Are you talking about the house?
I never wanted it.

40:06.780 --> 40:09.156
-It was you.
-No, no. It's you.

40:09.324 --> 40:12.785
That's not me you're looking at. It's you.

40:25.840 --> 40:28.675
Can you describe what you were feeling?

40:30.386 --> 40:31.845
I don't know.

40:32.013 --> 40:34.056
I got mad.

40:35.183 --> 40:36.725
At you.

40:45.235 --> 40:47.361
What were you thinking?

40:48.905 --> 40:51.323
-When you were recording my thoughts?
-Yeah.

40:52.367 --> 40:56.453
I was thinking about my new design.

40:56.621 --> 40:59.915
But he always ignores me, and it just...

41:00.083 --> 41:01.208
...made me furious.

41:06.881 --> 41:08.006
Feelings.

41:31.406 --> 41:34.408
KAREN:
It's hot off the mold. Take a look.

41:34.784 --> 41:37.911
-You're so selfish! You're arrogant!
-You're strangling me.

41:58.766 --> 42:00.601
I wanna ride my bike. Big deal.

42:03.771 --> 42:04.771
[CRYING]

42:04.939 --> 42:07.191
You take him. His pants are full.

42:10.028 --> 42:14.072
You could put flowers all around it.
I don't know what you're so upset about.

42:28.087 --> 42:29.796
[SINGING AND PEOPLE LAUGHING]

42:40.099 --> 42:41.433
Aha.

42:42.644 --> 42:44.937
KAREN:
You are a genius.

43:31.776 --> 43:33.402
[KNOCKING ON DOOR]

43:38.658 --> 43:40.492
I made that for you.

43:40.660 --> 43:42.536
It's a gift.

43:43.955 --> 43:45.497
What is it?

43:46.624 --> 43:48.166
It's me.

44:17.238 --> 44:19.448
MAN:
You may kiss the bride.

44:25.538 --> 44:27.539
[CHEERING]

44:33.379 --> 44:35.380
[SPEAKING INDISTINCTLY]

44:39.093 --> 44:41.261
MICHAEL:
That's where they flew.

44:41.429 --> 44:43.722
KAREN:
But what made them come here?

44:43.890 --> 44:45.891
It's the wind.

44:47.769 --> 44:49.478
The wind?

44:49.645 --> 44:51.021
It's constant here.

44:51.189 --> 44:53.899
He took off from the bottom of that hill.

44:54.067 --> 44:56.526
And the first flight...

44:56.694 --> 45:00.280
...was less than the wingspan
of a modern jet.

45:00.656 --> 45:04.076
And I wanna tell you something.
He was scared to death.

45:04.869 --> 45:07.287
I'm crazy about you.

45:07.455 --> 45:10.290
MICHAEL [WHISPERING]: It's a secret.
That's the girl I'm gonna marry.

45:13.211 --> 45:15.212
[LAUGHING AND SHRIEKING]

45:18.883 --> 45:20.217
[CHUCKLING]

45:35.191 --> 45:36.483
[MICHAEL CLEARS THROAT]

45:36.651 --> 45:39.528
We blew it, didn't we?

45:39.862 --> 45:41.947
We sure did.

45:43.658 --> 45:45.951
-I didn't get it.
-I didn't understand.

45:48.037 --> 45:50.539
Nothing's changed.

46:01.217 --> 46:03.593
You feel so good.

46:04.929 --> 46:06.847
MICHAEL:
So do you.

46:09.600 --> 46:11.601
[PIANO PLAYING]

46:54.979 --> 46:57.647
I never thought I could do this.

47:02.904 --> 47:04.905
[LAUGHING]

47:11.954 --> 47:13.955
[INAUDIBLE]

47:18.878 --> 47:20.754
-Oh!
-It always does that.

47:25.593 --> 47:27.385
-Try that.
-Oh.

47:27.970 --> 47:30.639
They're beautiful.

47:33.518 --> 47:36.269
Are you ready to take the plunge?

47:36.437 --> 47:37.771
Sure.

47:37.939 --> 47:39.940
[GIGGLING]

47:45.279 --> 47:47.280
[MICHAEL IMITATING FART NOISES
AND KAREN SQUEALS]

47:50.743 --> 47:53.828
MICHAEL:
Sing for me. Sing me that song.

47:53.996 --> 47:57.415
KAREN [SINGING]: In this place
We're all together now

47:57.583 --> 48:02.420
Figuring out and figuring out
Who's crazy

48:02.588 --> 48:05.382
And afterwards, we go out
And have a nice coffee

48:06.092 --> 48:09.469
And we smoke a cigarette
And make a dream

48:09.637 --> 48:12.681
That everybody in the world
Will feel good

48:12.848 --> 48:15.934
And they will be nervous no more

48:16.102 --> 48:18.770
And these are the hopes and the dreams

48:19.647 --> 48:22.315
Of beauty people like me

48:22.483 --> 48:24.317
And the other people

48:24.485 --> 48:26.570
It's so quiet.

48:27.697 --> 48:30.532
I was afraid you didn't like me anymore.

48:31.909 --> 48:33.577
Marry me.

48:35.705 --> 48:36.913
I will.

48:56.058 --> 48:57.851
CHRIS:
Mom?

48:59.353 --> 49:00.854
-Hi, Dad.
KAREN: Good morning.

49:01.022 --> 49:03.273
Hi, sport.

49:03.441 --> 49:06.151
I knew you couldn't live without us.

49:08.195 --> 49:10.071
-You want breakfast?
KAREN: Sure.

49:10.239 --> 49:12.282
MICHAEL: French toast.
KAREN: Orange juice.

49:12.450 --> 49:13.491
MICHAEL: Juice.
-All right.

49:13.659 --> 49:15.243
KAREN:
Bacon.

49:16.412 --> 49:18.413
[PHONE RINGING]

49:26.964 --> 49:28.006
Yeah?

49:36.223 --> 49:37.891
He's in the den.

49:38.059 --> 49:39.976
KAREN: Are you all right?
WENDY: He's out of control.

49:40.144 --> 49:42.395
KAREN:
But are you--? Are you okay?

49:45.024 --> 49:46.775
WENDY:
Karen, he's been down there all night.

49:46.942 --> 49:49.527
I thought he was reading
until I woke up this morning.. .

49:49.695 --> 49:51.571
...and I found him down there twitching.

50:07.338 --> 50:09.339
[GRUNTING]

50:32.905 --> 50:34.906
[BEEPING]

50:39.912 --> 50:41.871
Give it here.

50:45.376 --> 50:47.419
Give it, Michael.

50:48.295 --> 50:51.881
Please. Oh, God, please. Please.

50:52.049 --> 50:53.883
Please.

51:06.856 --> 51:08.440
Mike.

51:08.607 --> 51:10.775
We'll keep this between us, okay?

51:10.943 --> 51:12.694
MAN [OVER PA]:
Barometric pressure equalized.

51:12.862 --> 51:15.613
Dr. Brace, you may enter the chamber.

51:20.244 --> 51:21.828
Damn.

51:29.795 --> 51:31.337
HAL:
Hey, you wanna jog a few laps?

51:31.505 --> 51:33.631
No, not today, Hal.

51:34.383 --> 51:37.010
I don't know where I'm getting
all this energy.

51:38.846 --> 51:40.180
Well, you look good.

51:40.347 --> 51:44.184
I'll tell you, Mike, boy,
I'm getting a whole new outlook on life.

51:44.351 --> 51:46.728
I'm packing my bags
and leaving this place.

51:46.896 --> 51:48.188
Why is that?

51:48.355 --> 51:51.816
Hell, the good folks at the lab
are paying me disability leave.. .

51:51.984 --> 51:54.402
...of indeterminate duration.

51:54.570 --> 51:56.112
Is that good?

51:56.280 --> 51:59.407
Hell, it's the best piece of luck I’ve had.

51:59.825 --> 52:01.826
[BEEPING]

52:04.789 --> 52:06.456
What is it?

52:22.056 --> 52:25.225
Something happened to me.
It was more than just a sexual fantasy.

52:25.392 --> 52:29.020
It was a-- It was a feeling I had.

52:33.651 --> 52:35.568
I'm more than I was, Mike.

52:39.198 --> 52:40.323
More.

52:48.916 --> 52:50.041
MICHAEL [ON MONITOR]:
Thanks, Hal.

52:50.209 --> 52:53.378
Okay, make a dupe tape
and a transcript of that right away.

52:53.546 --> 52:54.963
You got it.

53:04.765 --> 53:06.975
MARKS:
Ten degrees right.

53:07.643 --> 53:09.394
Level.

53:09.562 --> 53:10.603
Good.

53:12.982 --> 53:14.983
[ENGINE HUMMING]

53:21.782 --> 53:24.450
WOMAN [OVER PA]: Altitude increased
to 50,,000 feet per minute.

53:25.619 --> 53:26.661
Now watch this.

53:26.829 --> 53:32.542
He can take a full 1 0-G rollout without
losing control, just by thinking about it.

53:33.168 --> 53:35.628
Bombs away, Gordon.

53:48.183 --> 53:50.184
[OPERA MUSIC PLAYING
OVER SPEAKERS]

54:35.189 --> 54:36.522
[GRUNTS]

54:38.567 --> 54:40.193
Damn.

54:50.537 --> 54:51.871
[GROANING]

55:05.886 --> 55:07.387
No!

55:07.805 --> 55:09.263
No.

55:11.350 --> 55:13.351
[CRYING AND GRUNTING]

55:24.989 --> 55:26.322
[SCREAMS]

55:33.330 --> 55:35.081
Mike.

57:11.136 --> 57:13.137
[GROANING]

58:32.676 --> 58:34.343
MICHAEL:
Lillian?

58:34.845 --> 58:35.887
Lillian!

58:36.096 --> 58:38.097
[ORGAN PLAYING]

58:45.689 --> 58:47.690
[CHOIR SINGING]

59:29.399 --> 59:31.275
I'll miss her.

59:32.819 --> 59:34.987
Talented lady.

59:35.155 --> 59:38.616
Impossible at times, but talented.

59:40.327 --> 59:42.995
The project's yours now, Mike.
It's up to you.

59:43.163 --> 59:45.248
Not now, Alex.

59:58.345 --> 1:00:02.348
Mike? This is it. I'm flying the coop.

1:00:03.684 --> 1:00:05.977
I just wanted to say goodbye.

1:00:09.022 --> 1:00:11.232
-Is that it?
-Yeah.

1:00:11.858 --> 1:00:14.944
-You gonna play it?
-No.

1:00:15.904 --> 1:00:17.905
She left it for you.

1:00:19.658 --> 1:00:21.867
I'll help.

1:00:28.000 --> 1:00:29.333
[CHUCKLES]

1:00:37.592 --> 1:00:39.593
[BEEPING]

1:00:47.519 --> 1:00:52.148
Dr. Marks, Dr. Brace
and Hal Abramson are in the lab.

1:00:59.406 --> 1:01:00.906
Go ahead.

1:01:23.889 --> 1:01:25.890
[GRUNTING]

1:01:28.769 --> 1:01:31.771
Maybe it's not a good idea, huh?

1:01:33.357 --> 1:01:35.191
MICHAEL [ON MONITOR]:
Well, wait a minute.

1:01:36.318 --> 1:01:39.111
I can rewire the output...

1:01:39.279 --> 1:01:40.446
...right here.

1:01:41.365 --> 1:01:44.533
Disconnect respiration, heart function...

1:01:45.660 --> 1:01:47.203
...right here.

1:01:47.371 --> 1:01:49.288
Give me that case.

1:01:52.125 --> 1:01:55.795
MARKS: Frank, please, get me Bob Jenkins,
Alex Terson. ..

1:01:55.962 --> 1:01:59.548
...Mr. Zimbach and Gordon Forbes
immediately.

1:01:59.716 --> 1:02:01.675
Yes. This is it.

1:02:29.287 --> 1:02:30.996
ALEX:
What is it?

1:02:31.164 --> 1:02:32.665
What is it?

1:02:38.713 --> 1:02:40.005
What, is he crazy?

1:02:40.173 --> 1:02:43.843
We do have a unique opportunity here.

1:02:44.010 --> 1:02:48.264
No, I can't authorize this. This is not
the research we're interested in.

1:02:48.432 --> 1:02:52.184
I'll take full responsibility, Alex.
There might be something on it we can use.

1:02:52.352 --> 1:02:55.729
The tap will be undetectable,
Gordon has the necessary experience.

1:02:55.897 --> 1:02:57.982
This is on your back, Jim.

1:02:58.150 --> 1:02:59.859
This is on your back.

1:03:10.078 --> 1:03:11.537
Dr. Marks?

1:03:11.705 --> 1:03:14.206
Um, Dr. Brace said something
about rewiring this output.

1:03:14.374 --> 1:03:16.125
Something about respiration and--

1:03:16.293 --> 1:03:18.878
I know what I'm doing, son.

1:03:31.975 --> 1:03:33.976
[SHRIEKING AND GROANING]

1:03:37.397 --> 1:03:39.398
[GRUNTING AND PANTING]

1:03:40.400 --> 1:03:42.526
What's happening to him?

1:03:46.406 --> 1:03:47.656
Shut it off, Landon.

1:03:50.535 --> 1:03:53.662
Shut it off! Goddamn it, shut it off.

1:04:04.007 --> 1:04:05.591
Jesus Christ.

1:04:37.499 --> 1:04:38.791
[CHUCKLING]

1:04:42.212 --> 1:04:43.462
-Ooh.
-Wow.

1:04:43.630 --> 1:04:45.381
Bet you I can do that.

1:04:45.549 --> 1:04:46.966
You can't do one more.

1:04:51.555 --> 1:04:54.723
You can't do it. Not one more.
You can't do it.

1:05:00.772 --> 1:05:02.106
Oh.

1:05:06.152 --> 1:05:08.404
-Have a Coke.
-You have a Coke.

1:05:08.947 --> 1:05:11.240
-Pow. Heh, heh, heh.
-Oh. God.

1:05:16.162 --> 1:05:18.163
No, no. Five minutes, please.

1:05:18.331 --> 1:05:19.498
It's important, come on.

1:05:22.502 --> 1:05:24.920
One cup of coffee. Come on.

1:05:27.507 --> 1:05:31.135
ALL:
Happy birthday, Lillian!

1:05:31.303 --> 1:05:32.553
[CHEERING]

1:05:32.721 --> 1:05:35.055
Come on. No, no. Come on.

1:05:35.223 --> 1:05:36.932
Happy birthday, Lillian.

1:05:40.729 --> 1:05:43.981
I gave you two years. I've been fighting
Washington for the last year.

1:05:44.149 --> 1:05:46.775
It's over. TRIAD is over,
don't you understand, Lillian?

1:05:46.943 --> 1:05:50.529
If it were up to me, I would give it to you.
But it's not up to me, babe.

1:05:50.697 --> 1:05:52.072
Now I have to go tell Michael.

1:05:52.240 --> 1:05:56.160
I've been with you. I've supported you.
I try to support you. What can I do?

1:06:01.750 --> 1:06:03.959
You don't look so well.

1:06:04.127 --> 1:06:06.086
Are things kind of tough for you?

1:06:06.254 --> 1:06:08.505
-I'm just tired.
-Tired?

1:06:10.383 --> 1:06:12.843
You know I work all the time.

1:06:13.011 --> 1:06:15.346
-But that's the way it's always been.
-Yeah?

1:06:16.723 --> 1:06:20.184
Do you know, I wonder sometimes
if there isn't something more than that?

1:06:22.020 --> 1:06:24.271
More than work? Not to me.

1:06:24.439 --> 1:06:28.067
Lillian, I have never broken my word
to you, but I'm sorry, it is dead.

1:06:29.069 --> 1:06:31.987
-You don't keep your promises.
ALEX: I have never broken my word.

1:06:32.155 --> 1:06:34.740
-I've never broken my word.
-We're so close.

1:06:35.075 --> 1:06:38.911
Well, I guess I wanna believe
there is more.

1:06:39.079 --> 1:06:40.788
Mike. Mike.

1:06:40.955 --> 1:06:43.415
-TRIAD is dead.
-I never could.

1:06:43.583 --> 1:06:45.000
It is dead.

1:06:45.210 --> 1:06:47.086
[BEEPING]

1:06:49.964 --> 1:06:51.965
Mike, I'm gonna shut it off.

1:07:01.393 --> 1:07:03.519
-You're fine.
-Chlorpromazine?

1:07:03.687 --> 1:07:05.479
It's okay.

1:07:06.773 --> 1:07:08.565
I promise.

1:07:09.275 --> 1:07:11.151
I'll never leave you.

1:07:13.530 --> 1:07:15.030
You feel better now?

1:07:15.824 --> 1:07:17.116
Michael.

1:07:17.283 --> 1:07:19.451
I want these personal experiments
stopped.

1:07:19.619 --> 1:07:22.413
You've abused your responsibility.

1:07:24.457 --> 1:07:26.458
You've endangered your life.

1:07:26.626 --> 1:07:28.919
I want a mind I can use.

1:07:29.087 --> 1:07:31.630
I don't want some kind of vegetable.

1:07:34.134 --> 1:07:36.593
The idea of playing that tape is sick.

1:07:36.761 --> 1:07:40.472
-It makes my skin crawl.
-Where is it?

1:07:42.851 --> 1:07:44.393
It's locked away.

1:07:44.561 --> 1:07:46.228
Secure.

1:07:46.396 --> 1:07:48.897
Alex, I told you, I wanna play it out.

1:07:49.065 --> 1:07:50.399
You didn't hear me, did you?

1:07:50.567 --> 1:07:51.984
Nobody plays that tape.

1:07:52.485 --> 1:07:53.819
Ever.

1:08:06.666 --> 1:08:11.003
MICHAEL: When I found her dead,
she was beautiful.

1:08:11.546 --> 1:08:14.506
But why do you have to die to let go?

1:08:16.718 --> 1:08:19.970
All my life I’ve had trouble with people.

1:08:20.138 --> 1:08:22.097
I didn't need them.

1:08:24.267 --> 1:08:26.143
Always had my own way.

1:08:26.311 --> 1:08:28.520
Total confidence.

1:08:29.522 --> 1:08:33.859
Now, because of this thing she left me,
this tape...

1:08:34.027 --> 1:08:36.153
... I'm scared.

1:08:38.072 --> 1:08:39.823
For the first time.

1:08:40.408 --> 1:08:42.493
I'm so scared.

1:08:44.871 --> 1:08:48.707
But the thing is, I like it. I want more.

1:08:51.586 --> 1:08:53.045
Look.

1:08:55.048 --> 1:08:58.634
You're married to the first man
in the history of the world.. .

1:08:58.802 --> 1:09:01.053
...who has the chance
to take a scientific look...

1:09:01.221 --> 1:09:05.224
...at the scariest thing
a person ever has to face.

1:09:05.391 --> 1:09:09.269
I've gotta do it. I've gotta play it.
Play that tape.

1:09:09.437 --> 1:09:11.021
And you'll have to help me.

1:09:11.648 --> 1:09:13.857
But you have to promise me.. .

1:09:14.025 --> 1:09:16.860
...that you'll never leave me again.

1:09:17.570 --> 1:09:19.154
I'm not going anywhere.

1:09:19.322 --> 1:09:20.489
Promise me.

1:09:27.288 --> 1:09:28.831
It's a deal.

1:09:35.880 --> 1:09:38.173
Look at those stars.

1:09:38.341 --> 1:09:40.300
KAREN:
Let's go to bed.

1:09:40.468 --> 1:09:42.094
MICHAEL:
Okay.

1:10:07.245 --> 1:10:09.246
But if you put the terminal box in here.. .

1:10:09.414 --> 1:10:11.623
...we're not gonna have any room
for processing.

1:10:11.791 --> 1:10:14.710
MAN: Put it next to the output dial.
-I don't want to see it.

1:10:14.878 --> 1:10:17.296
This is getting, you know. ...

1:10:18.339 --> 1:10:20.632
-What are you doing?
-No--

1:10:20.800 --> 1:10:23.218
Oh, Dr. Brace,
I'd like to introduce you to--

1:10:23.386 --> 1:10:25.554
Stop that. What are you doing?

1:10:26.264 --> 1:10:28.015
This is a valuable piece of equipment.

1:10:28.182 --> 1:10:30.642
We felt it should be protected
from unauthorized use.

1:10:30.810 --> 1:10:32.978
-Who is "we"?
-Well, the company.

1:10:33.146 --> 1:10:35.522
I work here too. It's my lab.

1:10:36.232 --> 1:10:40.611
Alex Terson has authorized me
to clean up after your sloppy work, Brace.

1:10:40.778 --> 1:10:42.571
Your notes are impossible to decipher.

1:10:42.739 --> 1:10:44.615
Yes, that's right.

1:10:46.159 --> 1:10:47.576
Oh, we'll figure it out.

1:10:47.744 --> 1:10:49.703
No, I don't think so.

1:10:50.705 --> 1:10:52.831
Take your hands off that.

1:10:52.999 --> 1:10:56.418
You can lock it up,
but you can't make it work.

1:10:56.586 --> 1:10:59.338
Get off it. Go on, get off.

1:10:59.881 --> 1:11:00.923
All of you, get out.

1:11:01.090 --> 1:11:03.425
-You've no right to be here. It's my lab.
-No.

1:11:06.638 --> 1:11:08.013
I'm sorry, Mike.

1:11:11.017 --> 1:11:12.017
No.

1:11:22.362 --> 1:11:24.404
MICHAEL:
Mind if I take a look?

1:11:25.031 --> 1:11:27.824
MAN: You know this security pass
expires tomorrow?

1:11:27.992 --> 1:11:30.160
Anyway, Dr. Brace,
you go through the door...

1:11:30.328 --> 1:11:33.372
-...take a hard hat and a pair of goggles.
-Thanks.

1:12:16.833 --> 1:12:21.086
MAN [OVER PA]: Dr. Brace,
please stand clear of the orange work zone.

1:13:20.146 --> 1:13:21.521
Hi, Hal.

1:13:21.689 --> 1:13:23.940
Michael. Gosh.

1:13:24.108 --> 1:13:26.735
-Hey, it's good to see you.
-Good to see you.

1:13:26.903 --> 1:13:29.488
You really had us worried, Mike.

1:13:30.281 --> 1:13:32.074
So playing a lot of golf.

1:13:32.241 --> 1:13:35.160
It's become a real whore to me.
I can't shake it.

1:13:35.328 --> 1:13:38.705
-Everything okay?
-Let me tell you, it's great.

1:13:38.873 --> 1:13:41.083
You know what I always wanted to be?

1:13:41.250 --> 1:13:43.794
A scientist, just like you guys.

1:13:45.838 --> 1:13:47.464
They locked me out, Hal.

1:13:51.219 --> 1:13:54.262
-I have to get back into the computer.
-It's illegal.

1:13:54.430 --> 1:13:56.932
Wouldn't want you to get in trouble, Hal.

1:14:00.103 --> 1:14:01.895
Hell, I don't care.

1:14:03.898 --> 1:14:06.066
Try "Brainstorm."

1:14:06.234 --> 1:14:08.860
It's in the open project file.

1:14:09.028 --> 1:14:11.029
Brainstorm.

1:14:11.781 --> 1:14:14.866
-Thank you.
-I'll do what I can to help you, Mike.

1:14:15.034 --> 1:14:16.660
Hey, Mike.

1:14:16.828 --> 1:14:18.829
Don't be a stranger.

1:14:41.477 --> 1:14:43.478
[BEEPING]

1:15:15.595 --> 1:15:17.387
Mr. Jenkins, you better get in here.

1:15:39.368 --> 1:15:41.328
Who do you think it is?

1:15:41.495 --> 1:15:43.538
I have an idea.

1:15:45.082 --> 1:15:46.958
Should I cut him off?

1:15:48.252 --> 1:15:50.587
No, let's see how far he gets.

1:15:50.755 --> 1:15:53.798
See if he's as good as he thinks he is.

1:15:56.886 --> 1:15:58.887
[KEYBOARD CLICKING]

1:16:02.767 --> 1:16:05.769
MICHAEL:
Flight data tape, adhesive tape.

1:16:05.937 --> 1:16:08.438
What's File DXO-9?

1:16:08.856 --> 1:16:11.233
He knows it's a code.

1:16:11.400 --> 1:16:13.401
He's trying to get in.

1:16:32.672 --> 1:16:34.798
-He's good.
-Ha, ha.

1:16:45.768 --> 1:16:47.519
MAN:
He's in.

1:16:49.105 --> 1:16:50.605
Son of a bitch.

1:16:51.315 --> 1:16:52.857
Dream states?

1:16:53.025 --> 1:16:54.693
Trauma.

1:16:54.860 --> 1:16:57.821
Physical pain threshold.

1:17:00.700 --> 1:17:02.617
Negative memory?

1:17:02.785 --> 1:17:05.036
Psychotic episode?

1:17:07.206 --> 1:17:08.290
Wait a minute.

1:17:25.308 --> 1:17:26.599
What do you want me to do?

1:17:26.767 --> 1:17:29.811
-Play it for him.
-Jimmy, load it up.

1:17:29.979 --> 1:17:32.314
Hey, whatever you want.

1:18:22.114 --> 1:18:24.574
In a few moments,
you will have an experience...

1:18:24.742 --> 1:18:27.452
...which will seem completely real.

1:18:27.870 --> 1:18:30.705
It will be the result
of your subconscious fears...

1:18:30.873 --> 1:18:34.751
...transformed to
your conscious awareness.

1:18:36.337 --> 1:18:40.465
Warning: This tape must not be played
by government personnel.

1:18:41.467 --> 1:18:45.804
It can be extremely harmful
and result in severe trauma.

1:18:46.597 --> 1:18:50.016
You have five seconds
to terminate this tape.

1:18:50.184 --> 1:18:55.939
Five, four, three, two, one.

1:18:56.107 --> 1:18:58.108
[SCREAMING]

1:19:26.178 --> 1:19:28.012
Alex sold us out.

1:19:28.180 --> 1:19:29.347
What?

1:19:29.515 --> 1:19:32.183
MICAHEL:
Lillian and I are working away.

1:19:32.518 --> 1:19:37.856
Alex turns the thing over to some covert
operation called Brainstorm Project.

1:19:38.023 --> 1:19:40.150
He's turned my work into something bad.

1:19:40.943 --> 1:19:44.112
Marks and a bunch of his people
are locking everything up.

1:19:44.280 --> 1:19:48.116
The production line's been retooled
to make military versions of the helmet.

1:19:48.284 --> 1:19:50.368
Hal just gave me a code name,
"Brainstorm"...

1:19:50.536 --> 1:19:53.663
...which has been a secret project
in the computer for weeks.

1:19:53.831 --> 1:19:55.665
It's bad, Karen.

1:19:55.833 --> 1:19:57.709
I just can't believe it.

1:19:57.877 --> 1:20:00.545
I never figured Alex could do
a thing like this.

1:20:00.713 --> 1:20:02.589
I can't believe this.

1:20:03.299 --> 1:20:06.384
They're using my invention
for brainwashing people.

1:20:06.552 --> 1:20:09.721
I just found a tape
of some kind of psychotic episode.

1:20:15.144 --> 1:20:16.603
If Marks is.. ..

1:20:16.770 --> 1:20:18.771
[CHRIS SHOUTING INDISTINCTLY]

1:20:33.412 --> 1:20:35.622
You wanna see something?

1:20:36.290 --> 1:20:38.416
I'll show you something.

1:20:43.839 --> 1:20:45.173
Now you're gonna find out.

1:20:49.094 --> 1:20:50.428
It's mine!

1:20:53.390 --> 1:20:55.141
What are you doing?

1:20:55.309 --> 1:20:58.603
Take that off. Chris?

1:20:59.271 --> 1:21:01.773
Don't scare me.

1:21:07.613 --> 1:21:10.365
Why don't you just take a seat here?

1:21:15.037 --> 1:21:17.288
This boy has had
a serious psychotic break.

1:21:20.125 --> 1:21:24.170
But he's gonna come out of it, isn't he?
I mean, he's gonna be okay?

1:21:24.338 --> 1:21:27.507
Yeah, he'll come out of it,
and he'll be okay.

1:21:28.509 --> 1:21:30.134
But you ought to go home and rest.

1:21:30.302 --> 1:21:33.680
Because we're gonna have to watch him
for two days under sedation.

1:21:33.847 --> 1:21:35.098
What do you think?

1:21:35.266 --> 1:21:37.433
Nothing like this
is ever gonna happen again.

1:21:37.601 --> 1:21:40.103
ALEX:
There they are. Hello, Karen. Michael.

1:21:40.271 --> 1:21:43.314
Dr. Pederson, this is Dr. Graf
from the Psychiatric Institute.

1:21:43.482 --> 1:21:45.275
What's the Brainstorm Project, Alex?

1:21:46.819 --> 1:21:48.778
Brainstorm? I don't know.

1:21:48.946 --> 1:21:51.656
You don't know? Have you seen my kid?

1:21:51.824 --> 1:21:53.491
They can't stop him shaking.

1:21:55.035 --> 1:21:56.160
Have you seen, Gordy?

1:21:56.328 --> 1:21:57.745
-No.
-He's dead.

1:22:00.082 --> 1:22:02.125
He monitored that tape, unauthorized.

1:22:02.293 --> 1:22:03.334
You plugged him in.

1:22:04.044 --> 1:22:05.461
I didn't plug him in, Michael.

1:22:05.963 --> 1:22:09.257
-And I've locked that tape up--
-Nobody locks me out.

1:22:10.134 --> 1:22:11.301
You need a rest, Michael.

1:22:11.468 --> 1:22:13.469
We'll take care of your son.

1:22:14.096 --> 1:22:16.347
-That tape is mine.
KAREN: Mike.

1:22:16.515 --> 1:22:17.890
Nobody locks me out.

1:22:18.058 --> 1:22:20.268
KAREN:
Mike, listen. He's right.

1:22:20.436 --> 1:22:23.438
You've gotta get away for a few days.

1:22:26.442 --> 1:22:28.818
Sure. Take a rest.

1:22:30.195 --> 1:22:31.279
KAREN:
Come on.

1:22:31.447 --> 1:22:34.365
Okay, okay. Take a rest.

